  <h2>Newfoundland and Labrador Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Newfoundland and Labrador is a true edge-of-season gardening region. Cool maritime air,
    frequent wind, and short frost-free windows mean most success comes from choosing the right crops,
    using protection when needed, and treating “average dates” as a rough starting point — not a promise.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Cool temperatures can limit heat-loving crops</h3>
  <p>
    Even when frost isn’t the immediate problem, cool days and colder nights can slow development for
    tomatoes, peppers, squash, and other warm-season crops. Many gardeners do best by focusing on
    cold-tolerant, quick-maturing plants and using the warmest microclimates available.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’ve ever planted something with a “short” maturity label and still struggled,
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">
      this explains why days-to-maturity can be misleading in cold climates
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Wind exposure changes everything</h3>
  <p>
    Coastal and open sites can be significantly harsher than sheltered yards, even within the same community.
    Wind strips warmth, stresses transplants, and increases moisture loss.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use shelter:</strong> fences, hedges, and garden walls can make a real difference.</li>
    <li><strong>Start strong:</strong> well-established transplants handle exposure better than tiny seedlings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3) Frost risk can return early</h3>
  <p>
    Late summer and early fall cooling often arrives quickly. That means late planting of warm crops is
    rarely reliable without a season-extension setup.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you want to stretch the season, this guide on
    <a href="/guides/how-to-add-2-to-4-weeks-to-your-growing-season/">
      adding 2–4 weeks to your growing season
    </a>
    covers the practical options.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Microclimates are your biggest advantage</h3>
  <p>
    The warmest gardens are usually those with sun exposure and wind protection: south-facing walls,
    sheltered courtyards, or spots that warm early and hold heat.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If your yard runs warmer or colder than nearby areas,
    <a href="/guides/why-your-backyard-may-be-warmer-or-colder-than-your-zip-code/">
      this explains what’s happening
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Use your nearest station data as a baseline — not a guarantee.</li>
    <li>Prioritize short-maturity crops and varieties.</li>
    <li>Plan protection if you’re pushing warm-season crops or late planting.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Newfoundland and Labrador, the best strategy is usually crop selection + microclimate + season extension.
  </p>
</section>